spanGrp.span: OK it's the thirty first of the seventh twenty seventeen with Alice Toka
on the fortune teller storyboard, Ranvetlam village, Fanbyak language
Two boys wanted to marry Meri.
Lobungbong man lo mwee lō, lom ramelole lob lene Meri.
One of them was called Jon, Jon was tall and thin.
Sōn nge san nge Jon, Jon mwebōlōōb rō mwewewaa nga.
Adam too was asking who will marry Mary.
Adam mōn ru muusi go abwelene Meri.
Mary stayed and was trying to think.
Then she went to a woman who can see the future.
Ngarō mean saale ven hol go ru mwesese silil.
She went and was sitting next to this woman and was asking, "If I take Jon, what will it be like?"
Mean ru mwetaa saale ven golē ru muusi, "ena uri Jon rō abwiir be?"
ah that's it now it's finished
Then she said to (her) that if she takes Jon
Ngarō mwigile vane go abuuri Jon
mm sapos yu mared long hem yu gat fulap pikinini
mm, if you marry him you will have many children
'if you, take, marry Jon, you will have many children
gile ob, euri, ob lene Jon samalō lobungbong abwee lon mele
no no yet, yu karem tu
no not yet, you've taken two
They stayed, they had many children
Go lō moso van, salalō lobungbong mwee lon mele
Mary was looking at a newspaper, she was reading it
Meri ru mwesese niuspeipa hal ru mwiridne
hal? maybe should have been hol 'one' - niuspepa and rid - Bislama
she saw that Adam died in
was thinking if she had taken
what would it have been like?
She went and saw the woman who sees the future again
mean se en ven go mwesese silil mōn
she went and sat, she was asking
"If I had taken Adam, what would it have been like?"
Rō ven gola ru mukulkulō usili
she said, "if you had taken Adam
she said that, "If you had taken Adam"
"you would have had lots of money"
"osa ma.. samalō mane tee tir... tee lon mele"
that woman was angry with Mary
mm bae, no be bae mi, sapos yu mared long hem bae mi kros wetem yi
If you had married him I would have been angry with you
[XX] "gile ah sam tu obleene, salalō, a lok tisili nak"
Mary said, "Why would you have been angry with me?"
Meri mwigile, "ben see nge lom ni, lom nisili nō?"
